  "enhanced_information": "Lipids absorbed in the intestine are primarily transported to the liver by chylomicrons. Chylomicrons are formed in the intestinal cells after dietary fats are processed and are released into the lymphatic system before entering the bloodstream. They carry dietary lipids, including triglycerides, to various tissues, including the liver. This process is well-supported by consensus in lipid metabolism literature, confirming that chylomicrons are the main vehicle for lipid transport from the intestine to the liver."
